      "motivation": "\n      <p><strong>Motivation.</strong> In textbook contract and mechanism design, the designer often knows the probability distribution, signal structure, or production technology. In applications, that knowledge is fragile: procurement costs are unknown, bidders have unknown information, workers' technologies are misspecified, and platforms observe only coarse data.</p>\n      <p><strong>Reality example.</strong> A regulator, platform, auctioneer, or principal may need a rule before knowing exactly how agents are informed. Robust theory asks for rules that keep a performance guarantee even under adversarial or ambiguous informational environments.</p>\n      <p><strong>Paper-specific angle.</strong> Explains why simple linear contracts can be optimal when the principal is uncertain about the agent's action technology.</p>\n    ",
      "medium": "\n      <p><strong>Big idea.</strong> Explains why simple linear contracts can be optimal when the principal is uncertain about the agent's action technology.</p>\n      <p><strong>Main result in words.</strong> A linear contract is max-min optimal in a broad moral-hazard environment because it gives a uniform incentive guarantee across many possible technologies.</p>\n      <p><strong>How to read it.</strong> Identify the designer's uncertainty set, the robust performance criterion, and the simple rule that survives the worst-case analysis.</p>\n    ",
      "deep": "\n      <h3>1. Environment</h3>\n      <p>The designer chooses a rule (m), which may be a contract (w), mechanism (M), auction format, pricing rule, or segmentation policy. The environment is not a single known model; it is an uncertainty set (mathcal U) of possible distributions, information structures, technologies, or communication devices.</p>\n      <div class=\"math\">\n        \\[\n          m^*\n          in\n          arg\\max_{m\\in\\mathcal M}\n          \\inf_{u\\in\\mathcal U}\n          W(m,u).\n        \\]\n      </div>\n      <p>Here (W(m,u)) is the designer's objective: profit, revenue, surplus, implementation success, or incentive provision.</p>\n      <h3>2. Paper-Specific Object</h3>\n      <p>Explains why simple linear contracts can be optimal when the principal is uncertain about the agent's action technology.</p>\n      <h3>3. Main Result</h3>\n      <div class=\"theorem-box\">\n        <h3>Robust Characterization</h3>\n        <p>A linear contract is max-min optimal in a broad moral-hazard environment because it gives a uniform incentive guarantee across many possible technologies.</p>\n      </div>\n    ",
      "example": "\n      <h3>Robust Linear Contract Example</h3>\n      <p>An agent chooses effort \\(a\\in[0,1]\\). Output is \\(y=a+\\varepsilon\\), but the principal is unsure about the distribution of \\(\\varepsilon\\). A linear contract pays \\(w(y)=\\alpha y+\\beta\\). If the agent's effort cost is \\(c(a)=a^2/2\\), the agent solves</p>\n      <div class=\"math\">\n        \\[\n          \\max_a \\alpha a-\\frac{a^2}{2}.\n        \\]\n      </div>\n      <p>The first-order condition is \\(a=\\alpha\\). Thus the share \\(\\alpha\\) implements effort without needing the full distribution of noise. The principal's robust problem chooses \\(\\alpha\\) to trade off incentive provision and rent/noise exposure.</p>\n    ",
      "technical": "\n      <p><strong>Contribution to literature.</strong> This paper is positioned against Bayesian contract/mechanism/pricing theory, where the designer solves an expected objective under a known prior. Its contribution is to weaken the informational assumption and characterize what can still be guaranteed.</p>\n      <p><strong>Proof technique.</strong> The common proof tools are max-min arguments, linear-programming duality, envelope/incentive constraints, Bayes-correlated-equilibrium obedience constraints, and extremal distributions that attain the worst case.</p>\n      <p><strong>Useful secondary technique.</strong> Look for the dual certificate: a simple contract or mechanism is robustly optimal because a worst-case environment and a dual bound meet at the same value.</p>\n      <p><strong>Problem solved.</strong> A linear contract is max-min optimal in a broad moral-hazard environment because it gives a uniform incentive guarantee across many possible technologies.</p>\n      <p><strong>Open questions.</strong> Important extensions include multidimensional types, dynamic learning about the uncertainty set, limited commitment, algorithmic pricing, privacy constraints, and empirical identification of the relevant uncertainty set.</p>\n      <p><strong>My comment.</strong> The reusable idea is to turn ignorance into a constraint set. A promising new paper often starts by changing (mathcal U): from unknown priors to unknown signals, from unknown signals to anonymous data, or from unknown technologies to misspecified agent beliefs.</p>\n    "
