      "deep": "\n      <h3>1. Environment</h3>\n      <p>The designer chooses a rule (m), which may be a contract (w), mechanism (M), auction format, pricing rule, or segmentation policy. The environment is not a single known model; it is an uncertainty set (mathcal U) of possible distributions, information structures, technologies, or communication devices.</p>\n      <div class=\"math\">\n        \\[\n          m^*\n          in\n          arg\\max_{m\\in\\mathcal M}\n          \\inf_{u\\in\\mathcal U}\n          W(m,u).\n        \\]\n      </div>\n      <p>Here (W(m,u)) is the designer's objective: profit, revenue, surplus, implementation success, or incentive provision.</p>\n      <h3>2. Paper-Specific Object</h3>\n      <p>Characterizes what monopoly price discrimination can achieve across all market segmentations consistent with aggregate demand.</p>\n      <h3>3. Main Result</h3>\n      <div class=\"theorem-box\">\n        <h3>Robust Characterization</h3>\n        <p>The feasible consumer-producer surplus set can be described by information-design geometry over market segments.</p>\n      </div>\n    ",
      "example": "\n      <h3>Robust Price Discrimination Example</h3>\n      <p>Half of consumers value the product at \\(1\\), half at \\(3\\). With one uniform price, revenue is</p>\n      <div class=\"math\">\n        \\[\n          R(1)=1\\cdot1=1,\\qquad\n          R(3)=3\\cdot\\frac12=1.5.\n        \\]\n      </div>\n      <p>Perfect segmentation charges \\(1\\) to low-value consumers and \\(3\\) to high-value consumers, giving</p>\n      <div class=\"math\">\n        \\[\n          R^{seg}=\\frac12\\cdot1+\\frac12\\cdot3=2.\n        \\]\n      </div>\n      <p>Robust pricing asks which surplus/revenue outcomes can be guaranteed across all segmentations or value distributions consistent with what the seller knows.</p>\n    ",
      "technical": "\n      <p><strong>Contribution to literature.</strong> This paper is positioned against Bayesian contract/mechanism/pricing theory, where the designer solves an expected objective under a known prior. Its contribution is to weaken the informational assumption and characterize what can still be guaranteed.</p>\n      <p><strong>Proof technique.</strong> The common proof tools are max-min arguments, linear-programming duality, envelope/incentive constraints, Bayes-correlated-equilibrium obedience constraints, and extremal distributions that attain the worst case.</p>\n      <p><strong>Useful secondary technique.</strong> Look for the dual certificate: a simple contract or mechanism is robustly optimal because a worst-case environment and a dual bound meet at the same value.</p>\n      <p><strong>Problem solved.</strong> The feasible consumer-producer surplus set can be described by information-design geometry over market segments.</p>\n      <p><strong>Open questions.</strong> Important extensions include multidimensional types, dynamic learning about the uncertainty set, limited commitment, algorithmic pricing, privacy constraints, and empirical identification of the relevant uncertainty set.</p>\n      <p><strong>My comment.</strong> The reusable idea is to turn ignorance into a constraint set. A promising new paper often starts by changing (mathcal U): from unknown priors to unknown signals, from unknown signals to anonymous data, or from unknown technologies to misspecified agent beliefs.</p>\n    "
